man <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"BUSSEY","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk, of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy, France: Boucé in Orne, from which came Robert de Buci mentioned in Domesday Book, Bouce (Manche), or Bucy-le-Long (Aisne). All are named with a Latin personal name <i>Buccius</i> (presumably a derivative of <i>bucca</i> ‘mouth’) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","English: variant of   Boosey  .","Americanized form of German   Busse  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessey","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): perhaps a variant of   Bussey  .","French: habitational name from any of the places in Côte-d'Or and Loire named Bessey, from the Gallo-Roman estate <i>Bassiacum</i>, from the Roman personal name <i>Bassius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."]},{"name":"Boosey","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>bosy</i> ‘ox-stall, cow-stall’ (Old English <i>bōsig</i>)."]},{"name":"Bussie","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bussey  , of Norman origin. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bucey","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Bussey  ."]},{"name":"Busey","meanings":["English: variant of   Bussey  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"WILLIAM","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir WILLIAM De BUSSEY was born in 1325, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir JOHN De BUSSEY, was 36 and his mother, Agnes de la Pole, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Isabelle Paynell. He died on 24 October 1380, in his hometown, at the age of 55, and was buried in Hougham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1325–24 October 1380":"1325–24. oktoober 1380","1325–1380":"1325–1380","1325–1375":"1325–1375","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1290–1349":"1290–1349","1300–1337":"1300–1337","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","24 October 1380":"24. oktoober 1380","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","29 September 1349":"29. september 1349","1290":"1290","Hougham, Lincolnshire, England":"Hougham, Lincolnshire, England","Hougham, South Kesteven District, Lincolnshire, England":"Hougham, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1325–24 October 1380":"1325–24. lokakuuta 1380","1325–1380":"1325–1380","1325–1375":"1325–1375","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1290–1349":"1290–1349","1300–1337":"1300–1337","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","24 October 1380":"24. lokakuuta 1380","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","29 September 1349":"29. syyskuuta 1349","1290":"1290","Hougham, Lincolnshire, England":"Hougham, Lincolnshire, England","Hougham, South Kesteven District, Lincolnshire, England":"Hougham, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1325–24 October 1380":"1325–24 octobre 1380","1325–1380":"1325–1380","1325–1375":"1325–1375","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1290–1349":"1290–1349","1300–1337":"1300–1337","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","24 October 1380":"24 octobre 1380","1300":"1